  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Girl&apos;s Right to Secondary Education (Tanzania)</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">In Tanzania, girls&apos;&apos; enrolment in secondary school is much lower than boys&apos;&apos;, and girls are more likely to drop out of school. Girls can face sexual harassment in the school and walking to and from school. Teenage pregnancies and HIV are common. African Initiatives supports local communities to construct and equip supervised girls&apos;&apos; dormitories in thirty secondary schools in two rural regions of Tanzania. They provide training for school management and local government committees tasked with community development. The project results in increased enrolment, retention and performance of girls in secondary schools and their protection from harassment and abuse. It has also established a far greater commitment towards girls&apos;&apos; education from community leaders. In addition to the project grant, African Initiatives has been awarded &#xA3;40,000 to help strengthen the organisation and their work, enabling them to support their local partners in Africa to continue to provide effective solutions to the issues they address.</narrative>
  </description>
